<DOCNO>FT924-5535</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKZCGACRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921126
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Market-Testing in Whitehall: Cold draught of competition in
Whitehall corridors - The implications for lawyers and accountants of the
government's proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ACCOUNTANTS and lawyers are geared up to compete for substantial contracts
as a result of the government's market-testing proposals.
The large accountancy firms have already been active in advising the public
sector on the scope for contracting out services. Now they are poised both
to advise and to take on the services themselves.
A number of firms have cut their teeth on advisory work for local government
and non-governmental organisations. They have also been active in the
growing private-sector market, offering accounting and tax compliance
functions previously run internally.
Many central government market-testing opportunities will be in similar
areas, covering internal audits, payroll, accounting and pensions
administration.
Most of the work to date has been strategic. Mr Malcolm Coster, head of
consulting at Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said his firm had won a contract from one
department worth nearly Pounds 1m to advise on quality assurance and the
supervision of its market-testing programmes.
The contracts themselves present more of a difficulty for the firms. Mr
Clive Williams, head of consulting at Ernst &amp; Young, rules out what he calls
the high-volume, low-value-added services many of the contracts would
involve. He said: 'Our strategy is to concentrate on advisory,
high-value-added work.'
Others are less adamant. Mr Brian Pomeroy, head of consulting at Touche
Ross, says his firm is already involved in financial management projects and
is looking at other areas. Mr Richard Gledhill of Price Waterhouse also does
not rule out competing for some market-tested functions.
Andersen Consulting has been particularly involved in running computer
systems contracted out from organisations such as the Stock Exchange, as
well as from companies such as BP.
The question is how far accountancy firms will be able to manage a highly
diverse workforce conducting relatively low-margin long-term work, in
contrast to their traditional higher-margin work by a relatively homogeneous
professional staff.
Lawyers in private practice have called the government's plans for
market-testing legal services unduly cautious.
Market-testing of legal services has been confined to conveyancing services
in the Department of the Environment, all legal services at the Department
of Social Security and services worth Pounds 30m, involving 1,400 mainly
administrative staff, at the Lord Chancellor's Department.
As part of a review of enforcement agents, the government is also planning
to contract out the work of county court bailiffs.
The government had been expected to go much further. The Health and Safety
Executive's routine health and safety prosecution work, the pollution
inspectorate's prosecution work and the Employment Department's local advice
work in the regions were all expected to be candidates for early market
testing.
City lawyers said yesterday the government's caution might stem from lack of
interest by the private sector in competing for government work.
One lawyer said that with such high overheads it was 'virtually impossible'
for central London law firms to make government legal work pay.
The white paper also confirms the government's intention to press ahead with
compulsory competitive tendering for local-authority white-collar services,
including 33 per cent of legal services.
Mr Paul Thomas, of the Law Society's local-government group, said
local-government lawyers had expected the extension of compulsory
competitive tendering to legal services.
Local-government lawyers were specialists in this area and were confident of
winning most of the available work.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-5536</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKZCGACQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921126
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Market-Testing in Whitehall: Courts Charter attacked for not
improving access to law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE much-delayed Courts Charter, published yesterday as part of the prime
minister's Citizen's Charter programme, was dismissed by lawyers and
consumer groups as a cosmetic exercise irrelevant to the real issue of
access to justice.
The charter, designed to guarantee national standards of service for court
users in England and Wales, was attacked by the Consumers' Association for
its failure to offer compensation to victims of administrative error by
court staff.
The Lord Chancellor's Department already pays compensation to people who
have suffered financial loss because of negligence by court staff. Last year
the department paid out almost Pounds 600,000, but the charter makes no
mention of entitlement to compensation.
Launching the charter, Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, said there was no
mention of compensation because when something went wrong it was more
important to put it right.
The Law Society said that while the commitment to clearer information for
court users and better procedures for handling witnesses and victims were
welcome, the charter was 'very disappointing'.
The society said it was sceptical about its benefits and surprised to find
no commitment to flexible court opening hours, the improving of case
listings, better accommodation for the disabled and the establishing of
court-based advice services for housing and debt.
Mr Paul Boateng, Labour's legal affairs spokesman, said the charter sought
'to hide an increasingly run-down and under-resourced justice system behind
a glossy veneer that bears no relation to the reality'.
The charter did nothing to address the central issue of equality under and
equal access to the law, he added.
