<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Market-Testing in Whitehall: Council reforms ahead of
Whitehall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPARED with local government, Whitehall is still in the
competitive-tendering stone age. For the past five years, the government's
compulsory competitive tendering (CCT) legislation has obliged local
authorities to put their main blue-collar services out to tender and many
have tendered white-collar services too.
Few authorities have taken contracting out as far as Berkshire county
council. Externalisation, in the Berkshire jargon, is its way of life.
Contracts of an annual value of more than Pounds 35m have been awarded to
outside contractors in the past five years.
Mr Tony Allen, the council's chief executive, said: 'It started in 1988 with
my ambition to get a grip on the management of the place rather than to
market-test services for the sake of it. But the whole process changed
direction once the government set its CCT timetable and obliged us to get on
with it anyway.'
Frontline as well as support services have been put out to tender - well
beyond the requirements of the legislation. Grounds maintenance, computer
support, supplies, cleaning, school meals, vehicle maintenance,
architectural design, quantity surveying, school music tuition, staff
training, highway maintenance and emergency services and forestry are all
out to the private sector. The county is contracting out highways and
planning and making a start on financial services.
The process has been controversial. Most of it took place under a Tory
administration and when the Conservatives lost their majority in a
by-election earlier this year, a halt was called to the contracting-out of
frontline services such as libraries and homes for the elderly.
Mr Allen respects the politicians' preferences but has no doubt that for
support services, at least, the benefits of tendering are undeniable. 'That
is even true of services which we run efficiently,' he said. 'Our own
local-government market is a shrinking one. Therefore if you have got a good
business, it will do better in an external market.'
When the internal team won the county's school meals contract, the county
sought to sharpen up the management and sold it to the BET group. Most local
authorities consider it a victory if the internal team wins a contract. Not
Berkshire.
In more than 90 per cent of cases, private contractors have employed the
former council staff when taking on a contract, almost invariably on similar
conditions of service.
'For that reason the process has not been acrimonious,' Mr Allen said. 'I
have been surprised at how quickly attitudes have changed: we've never
dubbed the process privatisation. It's externalisation - about changing the
management, not the service or necessarily the staff.'
The county's policy with each service to be tendered has been to separate
the staff concerned with strategy and to put the rest in a 'trading agency'
pending 'externalisation'. All services in trading agencies - which include
finance functions - will be subject to market testing.
Mr Allen said there were no differences of principle with contracting-out in
central government. 'And they have just as great a need to create more space
for strategic planning - the greatest benefit of externalisation. For too
long we have all been dominated by production planning problems.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
