<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Market-Testing in Whitehall: Government seeks to clarify
rights of employees in transfers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government acted yesterday to remove uncertainty about whether
regulations concerning the rights of employees when a business is
transferred still apply if public services are contracted out.
Mr William Waldegrave, the public service minister, used the launch of the
Citizen's Charter white paper to dismiss the discussion about the
application of the regulations as 'a complete red herring', and argued that
savings from contracting out to the private sector would still be achieved.
The uncertainty appeared to threaten the programme of market-testing
Whitehall services and the contracting out of local-government services.
The confusion stemmed from the EC Acquired Rights directive, intended to
secure the pay and conditions of workers who change employers in, for
example, acquisitions and mergers. Unions and some lawyers argued that the
directive applied when work was contracted out.
A recent ruling in the European Court of Justice indicated that UK
regulations putting the directive into practice were wrong to restrict
protection to workers in 'commercial ventures'. The threat of infringement
proceedings by the Commission prompted the Employment Department to amend UK
legislation to make clear that they applied to non-commercial undertakings.
The government's efficiency unit last week wrote to departments and
agencies, denying reports that the Foreign Office had suspended its
market-testing programme. The letter said the regulations had always covered
the public sector and that organisations tendering for public-sector work
had to take account of their possible effects.
Mr Waldegrave said the regulations applied only when an undertaking was
transferred. Whether they applied when delivery of a government service was
awarded to a private-sector tender or when a local-authority service was
contracted out would depend on the facts of the case.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
