<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Market-Testing in Whitehall: Computing services groups win
bonanza
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE UK-based computing services industry, the market testing programme
announced yesterday is a bonanza beyond their dreams.
It may eventually result in total fees of more than Pounds 750m flowing to
private-sector companies. Last year, total revenues of the 200-plus members
of the Computing Services Association (CSA), the trade body, amounted to
Pounds 4bn.
Market-testing will fundamentally redraw the profile of the industry and
relationships between established suppliers and government will change.
Internal operations that hold on to their department's business may emerge
as computing services companies in their own right.
Only a handful of companies operating in the UK are big enough and have the
capability to profit substantially from the windfall. The majority of them
are foreign-owned.
The Inland Revenue, for example, is seeking a single strategic supplier to
manage its Pounds 250m-a-year information technology budget.
The contract is expected to be in place by the end of 1993 and the value in
the first year is thought to be about Pounds 50m.
The Revenue is speaking initially only to companies with more than 20,000
staff worldwide. Only a large manufacturer could be expected to meet the
Revenue's conditions.
The contenders include International Business Machines and Digital Equipment
of the US, and ICL, now owned by Fujitsu of Japan.
Mr David Teague, ICL managing director for government business, said he
would be disappointed if his company did not win a share of the contracts on
offer at the Inland Revenue, Department of Trade and Industry, Home Office
and Customs and Excise.
Even large companies might find difficulties in meeting the contract
specifications, which imply moving computer staff from government to the
private sector; IBM is losing 40,000 staff worldwide and may not relish
adding several thousand Revenue personnel.
The large computing services companies - Andersen Consulting, Cap Sogeti
Gemini (in the guise of its UK subsidiary, Hoskyns), Computer Services
Corporation, Computer Management Group and Logica and Sema Group could
expect a share of the spoils. Intensive discussions are taking place to
establish consortia to bid for the larger contracts.
The larger concerns welcome the market-testing initiative, which will
increase market volume at a slack time for computing services, but there are
concerns based on a belief that the government has not fully thought through
the implications of outsourcing such sensitive services.
They question whether market testing is a fashion that will have to be
reversed in a few years as the close relationship between policy and data
processing becomes apparent.
One supplier said: 'At present, if ministers ask for information, civil
servants jump. It is not going to be like that again. Once data processing
skills are lost, they will be hard to replace.'
They are also anxious that the reputation of the industry might be damaged
if companies desperate for a share of government business quote
unrealistically low prices. Departments will have legal remedies against
unsatisfactory service, but may have a poor appreciation of the complexity
of moving from one supplier to another.
Questions have also been raised about what redress a government would have
if an internal department won a contract on a low bid and was unable to
fulfil its obligations.
Mr Colin Rowland, a director at Logica and chairman of the CSA, said
market-testing would lead to increased efficiency in government computing.
But some contracts were likely to be so big that only one or two companies
could hope to win them; that in itself would be anti-competitive.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
