<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Japanese workers lead on productivity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH FACTORIES lack skilled supervisors and are characterised by
in-fighting among shop-floor workers to curry favour with management, a
study from the institute says.
In a comparison of workforce characteristics at 10 UK plants run by Japanese
companies, the study says British workers are well behind their Japanese
counterparts in terms of productivity, solving problems, taking breaks from
work and identifying with the company line.
UK shop-floor employees score higher than their Japanese counterparts in
gaining qualifications, but that is mainly because these can act as
passports to better jobs with other companies.
More encouraging for the UK is that some aspects of the Japanese work ethos
seem to be taking root in the 10 Japanese 'transplants'.
The study does not identify the companies concerned but says they are mainly
in electronics and car manufacturing.
The study says that in the transplants 'the rate of knowledge acquisition by
UK workers was broadly comparable with that in Japan'. It adds that while
British employees have also taken on some of the competitive characteristics
of their Japanese counterparts, in terms of wanting to outperform rival
companies.
Skilled factory supervisors - the all-rounders of the production line who
link between management and machine operators - are, however, 'almost
impossible to find' in the UK. The study defines a good supervisor as
someone familiar with technology, machines and production practices who is
skilled in human relations and good at creating a team spirit.
The study says a typical UK manufacturing employee who hits on new insights
into production processes tends to keep such facts to him-self.
That is done 'so as to boost his personal standing with the company relative
to his fellows'.
Workers in the Japanese transplants have improved in that area, being keener
to share ideas after having learnt something about the value Japanese
companies give to teamwork.
In seven of the 10 plants, productivity was lower than the equivalent
factories run by the same companies in Japan.
UK workers beat their Japanese equivalents in terms of productivity in only
one case.
British shop-floor employees scored poorly in their ability to repair faults
on the production line or use their initiative to maintain plant to stop it
breaking down. They tended to seek excuses to take a rest from work, such as
during a breakdown or a component shortage.
The study emerged from detailed questioning of Japanese and British managers
in the plants about how equivalent sets of workers com-pared in Japan or the
UK.
</TEXT>
