<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Recovery 'unlikely until 1994'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECOVERY from the recession is unlikely until 1994, an assessment of
economic prospects published today by PA Cambridge Economic Consultants
suggests, Peter Marsh writes.
House prices will continue to fall next year while the boost to exports
arising from the pound's devaluation will come through only slowly, PA says
in a report produced with Cambridge University's Department of Land Economy.
The large volume of debts built up by consumers and companies since the late
1980s will constrain any recovery while unemployment will continue to rise
next year, sapping overall confidence.
There will be little extra boost to demand from public spending, because the
poor state of government finances will mean the Treasury wants to hold back
state spending as much as possible.
Cambridge Economic Review, vol Two, Cambridge Economic Consultants, 62 Hills
Rd, Cambridge CB2 1LA. Pounds 32 inc postage.
