<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM to speed up search for EC deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR will accelerate his tour of European capitals this weekend in
an effort to improve the chances of deals' being reached by EC leaders at
next month's Edinburgh summit.
The prime minister expects to visit six capitals in three days, starting
tomorrow, in an attempt to forge a consensus on the future financing of the
community and possible Europe-wide economic growth initiatives. He will also
want to discuss how Danish objections to the Maastricht treaty can be
accommodated.
Downing Street officials conceded that it was 'partially coincidental' that
visits to the most crucial countries - France, Germany and Denmark - have
been left until nearer the Edinburgh summit.
They said Mr Major's meeting in Madrid on Tuesday with Mr Felipe Gonzalez,
the Spanish prime minister, might also prove critical. Spain has put an
emphasis on securing 'cohesion funds' for poorer EC countries and is
suspicious of attempts to define 'subsidiarity' - the principle of
decisions' being made at the lowest possible level of government - which Mr
Major needs to sell the Maastricht treaty to Tory Euro-sceptic MPs.
Downing Street also believes that the French government, although concerned
about the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, will be supportive in
resisting large increases in the EC budget.
Mr Major will visit Rome and Athens tomorrow, returning to London early on
Saturday. On Monday he travels to Luxembourg and probably The Hague and then
leave for Madrid in the evening. He will visit Lisbon on Tuesday. Mr Major
went to Brussels on Monday. Trips to Paris, Dublin, Copenhagen and Bonn have
yet to be arranged.
The prime minister has already phoned Chancellor Kohl in Germany. Mr Major
is not expected to visit any capital more than once before the Edinburgh
summit. Mr Major is also keen for the summit to discuss the completion of
the single market, enlargement of the EC and Gatt. The Commons will begin
the committee stage of the Maastricht bill next week.
</TEXT>
