FT  26 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Treasury hints at economic decline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY is near to admitting that Britain's long-term potential to
produce goods and services has been damaged by the lingering recession,
Treasury officials indicated last night, Peter Marsh writes.
Giving evidence to the Commons Treasury and Civil Service committee,
Professor Alan Budd, the Treasury's chief economic adviser, also suggested
that unemployment was likely to continue rising through next year. It would
be 'many years' before the government's finances returned to surplus.
The new assessment by Treasury officials of the longer-term effects of the
recession is the gloomiest indication that the Treasury has given so far
into the economic decline that Britain faces deep-seated economic problems.
Mr Chris Riley, the Treasury official in charge of medium-term policy
analysis, said it was 'quite possible' that in the budget next March the
Treasury would revise down its long-term projections about the potential of
the economy.
