<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Commons endorses plan to freeze
MPs' pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPS VOTED themselves a year-long pay freeze in the Commons last night after
the government appeared to indicate they would receive an increase of at
least 3.9 per cent from January 1994.
A government motion advocating the freeze was convincingly carried by 321
votes to 103, a majority of 218.
Opposition MPs who voted against pegging next year's salary at Pounds 30,854
included former shadow cabinet members Mr Gerald Kaufman and Mr Roy
Hattersley as well as Sir David Steel of the Liberal Democrats.
The government had previously staved off defeat on a cross-party amendment
advocating that for pension purposes, MPs should be treated as if they had a
1.5 per cent pay increase from January instead of a freeze.
This was defeated without a vote after Mr Tony Newton, leader of the
Commons, offered to consult with MPs' representatives over the possible
alternative of 'building on' general provisions for additional voluntary
contributions in pension schemes generally.
That approach, he suggested, might better resolve the difficulties the
amendment was designed to address by guaranteeing MPs a return on any
additional money they might wish to contribute.
Opening the debate, Mr Newton said that the government accepted the need for
a clear link between MPs' salaries and an accepted Civil Service grade.
However, the growing role of performance-related pay in the Civil Service
meant that changes to existing arrangements - implemented in 1987 - were
necessary.
The government had 'no wish' to return to the situation where MPs had to
decide on their own level of pay each year, Mr Newton said.
On the basis of the link established by the 1987 resolution, backbenchers
would have received a 3.9 per cent increase this year to Pounds 32,057.
Mr Newton said the government did not wish MPs to be permanently
disadvantaged by 3.9 per cent in relation to civil servants, implying they
may get a rise of at least this magnitude from January 1 1994.
He said that restraint in public expenditure was 'a necessary condition' of
the government's ability to direct resources to areas of spending which
should 'rightly be priorities'.
He reminded MPs that public-sector pay rises were being limited to a maximum
of 1.5 per cent for the year ahead. It was 'right for the government and the
House as a whole to give a lead in exercising restraint'.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, claimed the government was
trying to use MPs as a 'stalking horse' to attack and undermine the position
of others in the public sector.
By freezing MPs' pay, the government hoped to create 'an illusion of
fairness - that the highest paid are taking their fair share,' she argued.
In fact, senior civil servants and judges would next year receive more than
MPs and more than 1.5 per cent.
Mrs Beckett urged MPs to consider their overall incomes before they voted.
More than 50 of the Tory backbenchers who signed a Commons early day motion
in support of the government's position had other declared interests.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
