<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Deficit in motor trade widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK motor industry trade balance deteriorated sharply in the third
quarter with the deficit increasing by 154 per cent to Pounds 1.2bn from
Pounds 471m in the same period a year before.
The deficit in cars, commercial vehicles and automotive parts and
accessories in the first nine months rose by 131 per cent to Pounds 2.56bn,
more than double the deficit for the whole of last year.
The motor industry alone accounted for more than a third of the total UK
visible trade deficit of Pounds 3.25bn in the third quarter.
The performance has worsened in the face of faltering exports of automotive
products and a rapid rise in the value of imports.
The Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders warned that 'it may be some
time yet' before the motor industry trade balance benefited from the
devaluation of sterling.
The value of automotive imports continued to rise with a jump of 22 per cent
in the third quarter. The SMMT warned yesterday that 'stocks of imported
cars must already be at relatively high levels and any further growth could
result in serious stock problems in coming months.'
