<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Homes raided as police probe Alan Paul chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE investigating the collapse last year of the Alan Paul hairdressing
and cosmetic shop franchise chains yesterday raided 13 homes or offices of
directors and senior employees in Merseyside, Cheshire and Greater
Manchester.
The raids, by 75 officers from several police forces, were led by Detective
Chief Superintendent Bill Coady, head of Merseyside's fraud squad. Police
removed papers and records but there were no arrests.
Homes raided included those of Mr Alan Moss, the company's former chairman,
and Mr Mike Rowlands, the managing director.
Police said yesterday they were investigating possible 'financial
irregularities' in the running of Alan Paul and the 'circumstances
surrounding the company's rights issue' of July last year. The issue flopped
with only a 15 per cent take-up, and the subsequent slide in the share price
led to Alan Paul shares being suspended, followed by receivership. Alan
Paul's rise was one of the more noticeable small-business growth stories of
the 1980s, partly because of the flamboyance of Mr Moss and Mr Rowlands -
they encouraged franchisees to emulate them by driving BMWs and Ferraris -
but also because the company became Britain's only quoted hairdresser.
It floated on the unlisted securities market in 1989 and Mr Moss, who
founded the business in Bromborough, Wirral in 1970, celebrated with a
personalised number plate for his red Ferrari, USM 1.
Expansion was via franchising and taking over other chains. The group
included Body &amp; Face Place cosmetics shops. From 60 outlets on flotation the
group grew to 542 shops and salons.
The failed rights issue, a profits warning and two changes of chairman in
two months led to shares being suspended a year ago at 20p. They had floated
at 140p and peaked at 166p.
Coopers &amp; Lybrand, appointed receiver in December last year, contacted the
police in February.
</TEXT>
