<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / MPs told of risk to BR routes in south
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SEA CONTAINERS, the Bermuda-based shipping, ferry and hotel group, warned
yesterday that 5 per cent of British Rail's routes would have to close if
railways were to become profitable after privatisation.
Mr James Sherwood, Sea Containers' president, told MPs that early candidates
in the Network SouthEast area would include the North Downs line between
Reading and Tonbridge and the Sussex Coast line between Brighton and
Hastings.
Sea Containers has told the government that it is interested in taking on
the franchise for the operation of Network SouthEast's passenger train
services between London and the south coast after privatisation.
Mr Sherwood told the Commons transport committee that three conditions would
have to be fulfilled if costs and revenues were to make the operation
viable:
Sea Containers would want control of the tracks as well as the trains
because it would need to secure reductions in track costs.
Mr Sherwood calculated that there was scope for savings of Pounds 50m a
year.
Double-decker trains would have to be introduced to increase revenues
because existing track and train capacity was full and higher fares would
result in loss of traffic to road transport.
Under-used lines would have to close because they were losing too much
money.
'At the moment, British Rail is spending tens of millions of pounds a year
running services that no one wants,' Mr Sherwood said.
He added that if the government wanted loss-making services to run, it would
have to subsidise them. But he said he believed the government intended to
phase out subsidies.
Three other prospective train operators appearing before the committee lent
some much-needed support for the government's privatisation proposals, but
each wanted adjustments to the proposed regime.
Mr Richard Branson, chairman of Virgin Group, said he was interested in
providing inter-city services on routes similar to those now operated by
short-haul aircraft.
The biggest single issue facing his company and other train operators was
how much they were going to be charged for the use of the tracks.
Mr Branson said rail could not compete with road at present because train
oper-ators had to pay very heavy track costs while road users enjoyed free
access to the highways.
'Are they going to continue to subsidise road at the expense of rail or are
they going to balance the books?' he asked.
'If they are going to balance the books, it will make entry that much
easier.'
Two bus companies, Stagecoach and Yorkshire Rider, broadly supported the
government's proposals but wanted Railtrack, the track-owning authority, to
be decentral-ised so that its boundaries matched those of the franchise
areas.
Stagecoach said it wanted that to be a transitional step leading to the
eventual takeover of the tracks by franchisees.
</TEXT>
