<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Bloodstock VAT change 'threatens jobs'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD and BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of jobs could be lost in the British horsebreeding industry under
a value added tax regime to be introduced on January 1, a cross-party
committee of MPs heard yesterday.
Mr Christopher Haines, chief executive of the Jockey Club, told the Commons
employment committee the VAT charges were the reason why Tattersalls, the
UK's largest bloodstock auctioneer, was moving its most prestigious sales to
Ireland, where VAT is almost 15 percentage points lower than in the UK.
Tattersalls said yesterday it had previously believed that horses brought
from Ireland or France for sale at Newmarket would be liable for VAT at
rates applying in their country of origin, but it now appears that VAT will
be charged at the full UK rate.
The racing world has been warning for some time that the UK was in danger of
losing its position as a centre for horse breeding and sales.
Racing trade organisations say the UK's high level of VAT, at 17.5 per cent,
is driving buyers to Ireland, where VAT is 2.7 per cent, and to France, with
its 5.5 per cent rate.
The government has refused a request from horsebreeders to impose a lower
rate of VAT or to register them for VAT - as occurs in France - which would
mean they would get the VAT they pay back.
Horsebreeders claim they will be at a disadvantage with competitors
including France, which Mr Haines said was more flexible.
He said: 'We are playing Marquess of Queensberry rules with people who are
not doing so.' The British government had been slow to heed the threat to an
industry that provided employment for 30,000 people directly and 100,000
indirectly.
Tattersalls said most of its auctions would still be held at its
headquarters in Newmarket.
The move to Ireland applies only to the top-of-the-market Houghton yearlings
sale, where prices are over Pounds 20,000, and the tax differential has hit
particularly hard.
Houghton sales account for about a third of Tattersalls' turnover, which was
Pounds 53m last year and is expected to fall to Pounds 35m this year.
The absence of Arab buyers - previously big spenders at Newmarket - from
October's Houghton sale was blamed on the high tax levels.
They were well represented at the Irish sales soon after.
Britain's betting industry is pressing the government to relax restrictions
that prevent betting shops opening in the evening.
A Gallup survey sponsored by the Betting Office Licensees Association shows
that most customers want betting shops, which at present must shut at
6.30pm, to remain open to cover evening racing in the summer and satellite
televised races at other times of the year.
It is argued that the exchequer, which at present collects Pounds 500m a
year in duty from the betting industry, would be a big beneficiary as
turnover would increase by at least 10 per cent if evening opening were
allowed, bringing in an additional Pounds 50m or more in tax.
Evening opening would also secure current employment and create a
substantial number of jobs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
