<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Record rise in cable services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE cable television industry has enjoyeda record period of growth, the
Independent Television Commission said yesterday.
In the three months to October, 49,667 new subscribers were connected,
bringing the total in the previous 12 months to 159,569. Both figures were
records.
The quarterly ITC figures show that the total number of subscribers to
modern multi-channel cable systems rose to 380,297 with cable operators,
mainly North American, accelerating their building of cable networks.
Cable services are available to 1.75m homes. The penetration rate - the
proportion of those who subscribe out of those who could do so - is 21.7 per
cent, an increase of 2.8 percentage points over the year. The ITC believes
the cable audience exceeds 1.2m.
The most striking growth was in cable companies offering telephone services
as well as television.
Of the 57 operating franchises, 21 are offering a telephone service, almost
all in competition with British Telecom.
In the year to October, the number of telephone lines installed by cable
companies rose from 11,903 to 72,681.
Sir George Russell, chairman of the ITC, said earlier this week that by the
end of the year investment in cable would exceed Pounds 1bn.
The ITC chairman also quoted Saatchi &amp; Saatchi forecasts that by the turn of
the century 7.6m people would be receiving cable services and that 70 per
cent of the country would be covered.
</TEXT>
