<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Lloyd's elects Rowland to council
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS of Lloyd's of London yesterday voted Mr David Rowland to the
insurance market's governing council, clearing the way for his expected
election by 20 fellow council members to the post of chairman next week.
The council votes on Wednesday, although Mr Rowland will not be confirmed as
chairman in succession to Mr David Coleridge until the new year. Mr Rowland,
59, has spent most of his working life at Lloyd's. He announced his
resignation as chairman of Sedgwick Group, the insurance broker, earlier
this year.
Mr Rowland topped the poll of working Names - those who have jobs with
brokers and agencies in the market - winning 2,818 votes. Mr Robert Hiscox,
managing director of the Roberts &amp; Hiscox agency, came second with 2,283
votes.
Also elected were Mr Stephen Merrett and Mr Richard Keeling, both prominent
underwriters, with 1,513 and 1,214 votes respectively. Mr Hiscox and Mr
Merrett were members of a 14-strong market task force chaired by Mr Rowland
that proposed wide-ranging reforms at Lloyd's in January.
Mr David James, a 'company doctor' who is chairman of Lep Group, Eagle Trust
and Davies &amp; Newman, was also elected to the council.
Mr James topped the poll of outside Names with 4,230 votes. His closest
challenger was Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, chairman of the Gooda Walker Names
Action group, with 3,598 votes. He failed to gain election to the council.
The Association of Lloyd's Members (ALM), the biggest Names organisation,
which represents 9,000 of Lloyd's 22,400 Names, backed Mr James's candidacy.
Its chairman, Mr Neil Shaw, welcomed the result: 'David Rowland's election
means that Lloyd's top team is now in place. The ALM looks forward to
working with them to build a successful Lloyd's and to handle the problem of
damaged Names in the most sympathetic way possible without being unfair to
the majority.'
</TEXT>
