FT  26 NOV 92 / Chicago airport backed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ILLINOIS Governor Jim Edgar has outlined a plan to locate a third
international airport in the Chicago area near rural Peotone, disregarding
criticism that it would be too far away and would not draw airlines or
passengers, AP reports from Chicago.
The Dollars 1.8bn (Pounds 1.2bn) plan includes proposals to build an
additional runway to relieve congestion at Chicago's O'Hare International
Airport and create a Dollars 423m high-speed rail system linking down-town
Chicago to the proposed new airport about 35 miles away.
The airport would create 102,000 construction jobs and 167,000 permanent
jobs by 2020, Mr Edgar said.
The Illinois Senate turned down an earlier proposal for a Dollars 10.8bn
airport, for which Chicago Mayor Richard Daley fought for three years.
