<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / World Trade News: Farmers clash with riot police in Paris
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than 50 French police were injured yesterday in clashes with
demonstrators as French farmers massed in Paris to protest at the European
Community trade agreement with the US.
CRS riot police fired tear gas and made repeated charges at militant farmers
who in turn let off fireworks and threw iron bars and crowd-control
barriers. Five police were taken to hospital and 12 protesters were
arrested. By last night the crowd was dispersing.
Earlier about 3,000 farmers had converged on the Esplanade des Invalides and
the nearby National Assembly as parliament debated whether to reject the
accord. Workers at the National Assembly peered nervously out of windows
behind the safety of police barriers.
Trading was interrupted on the Paris Stock Exchange when farmers broke in,
unfurling banners and setting off firecrackers.
Coachloads of farmers from all over France poured into the Invalides
throughout the afternoon. They chanted anti-American slogans and carried
banners emblazoned with 'Tomorrow, US food, Japanese cars, Asian textiles
and French job losses' and 'No to the US green army'.
An elderly farmer stared forlornly at the scarred shields of the riot
police. 'Whatever happens, French farming is finished,' he said. 'It's not a
question of whether we'll be ruined, but of when. That's why we can't give
up without a fight.'
There were other demonstrations elsewhere in France. Farmers in
Clermont-Ferrand burnt piles of tyres outside the local McDonald's fast-food
store in protest against the US-owned group and the British flag was burnt
in Boulogne and Calais.
Farmers blockaded the home of Mr Andre Bourgeois, Belgium's agriculture
minister, late yesterday and set tyres alight in the street in protest at
the trade deal, Reuter reports from Brussels, quoting a local news agency.
Paramilitary police moved the 200 farmers and their 50 tractors.
</TEXT>
