<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / ERM turmoil hastens day of a two-speed Europe: Some European
officials expect to see a fixed exchange rate D-Mark bloc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recent turmoil in the European exchange rate mechanism has hastened the
advent of a two- or multi-speed Europe, according to monetary officials in
several continental European countries.
The officials, of the 'core' countries of the European Monetary System, are
quietly optimistic that currencies grouped around the D-Mark will be able to
form a bloc in which parities stay virtually unchanged once the turbulence
on currency markets dies down.
But despite last weekend's devaluations of the Spanish peseta and Portuguese
escudo, there is much less confidence that the Iberian currencies or the
British pound and the Italian lira, which at present are floating outside
the ERM, will be able to maintain stable relationships with the other EMS
currencies.
In a number of conversations since the weekend realignment, the officials,
who declined to be identified, said that they did not believe that the
recent upheavals in the ERM meant the end of the system.
However, most accepted that the dislocation of the ERM in the successive
waves of speculation since early September had made the achievement of
economic and monetary union in line with the Maastricht Treaty less certain
and at least subject to delay.
But unlike London-based analysts who have forecast the collapse of the ERM,
the continental monetary officials are looking ahead to a period in which
economic fundamentals, such as inflation and trade performance and
international competitiveness, will play a bigger part than in the past in
determining currency relationships in Europe. As a result, Germany, France,
the Benelux countries, and possibly Ireland and Denmark, will effectively be
able to form a fixed exchange rate bloc. Austria, which links its currency
to the D-Mark, would also be a member of this group.
There are still battles to be won, notably convincing financial markets that
the Danish krone and Irish punt are not candidates for devaluation. The
scale of speculation in such small currencies can be spectacular. In three
hours last Friday, for example, the Belgian National Bank had to buy Dollars
1bn worth of Irish punts.
But trading in the Danish and Irish currencies, as well as the French franc,
was calmer yesterday. This prompted hopes that the speculators may have been
deterred by the resolute action taken in all three countries to raise
interest rates since Monday.
While officials generally expect the inner group of ERM countries to emerge
as a recognisable and cohesive group of countries, there are differences
about the implications of such a development for Emu.
French monetary officials believe that the recent crisis in the ERM has
underlined the need for monetary union among those countries with convergent
economic conditions. 'There would have been no crisis between the French
franc and the D-Mark if they were a single currency,' observed one official
in Paris. 'So long as there is real convergence, it should be a case of the
quicker the better in turning the EMS into a single currency system.'
Germany, however, is far more cautious. Earlier this month, Mr Hans
Tietmeyer, the Bundesbank vice president, warned against too rapid a move to
Emu. He told an audience in southern Germany that the premature creation of
a single European currency and central bank could be threatened by tensions
in pay developments and fiscal policy.
Fears about sharply rising German wages have been expressed by Mr Alfons
Verplaetse, the Belgian National Bank governor. In an interview with the
German newspaper Handelsblatt, he said he regretted that the Maastricht
convergence criteria made no reference to income trends and advocated an
incomes policy for Germany.
Indeed, while monetary officials in the EMS core countries are looking to a
future in which their currencies stay closely linked to the D-Mark, there is
strong underlying concern about economic developments in Germany.
High labour costs and relatively high inflation compared with countries such
as France, Denmark and Ireland, have caused Germany to lose competitiveness.
The cost of subsidising the new eastern Lander and Germany's continuing high
budget deficits have caused some officials to wonder whether the German
economy will be able to fulfil the Maastricht convergence criteria by the
end of 1996, when the EC is due to assess whether a majority of its member
states is willing and able to embark on Emu.
The consensus among senior officials is that Germany will be able to
overcome its difficulties. But one noted that the D-Mark really should
devalue against the French franc and other ERM currencies because of
Germany's declining competitiveness.
Samuel Brittan, Page 21
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
