<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Ratner quits retail group after shareholder pressure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GERALD RATNER, the jeweller who became famous for applying the
description 'crap' to one of his products, has quit the ailing retail group
which bears his family name.
He follows many other retail personalities who flourished in the 1980s
consumer boom but have since been deposed, such as Sir Ralph Halpern of
Burton and Mr George Davies of Next.
In a prepared statement, Mr Ratner said: 'I am obviously saddened to be
leaving a business of which I am so proud. However, the continuing negative
press I have attracted leads me to believe that this decision is in the best
interests of the group and the people working in it.'
Mr Ratner is thought to have felt under pressure from the group's bankers
and shareholders. At the annual meeting in September, shareholders called
for his resignation.
Mr Jim McAdam, Ratners' chairman, who will now take over Mr Ratner's role as
head of the group's UK jewellery business, said Mr Ratner's departure was
'very much his own decision'. Mr Ratner will receive compensation of Pounds
375,000, equivalent to a year's salary.
Although Mr Ratner's departure had been discussed internally for some time,
it was only agreed yesterday. Ratners' fall from grace follows a familiar
pattern of companies which expanded too aggressively, financed by
borrowings, and failed to anticipate the recession.
Its profits grew from almost nothing in 1984, when Mr Ratner took charge of
the group from his father, to a peak of Pounds 130m in 1990. He expanded in
the UK, acquiring chains such as H. Samuel and Ernest Jones, and into the US
with the purchase of Sterling and Kays Jewellers. The group's stock market
value peaked at Pounds 840m in June 1990, just before the Kays deal was
agreed. From there the slide was rapid. Yesterday the shares closed at 18p,
down 1p, valuing the company at Pounds 52.7m. News of his departure came
after the market closed.
Mr Ratner was credited with changing UK jewellery retailing from a staid
business with customers making rare but expensive purchases to a fashion
business. Ratners' extensive use of 9-carat gold and the development of
devices such as hollow earrings, brought the prices into the range of
everyday purchases.
But Mr Ratner's fate was sealed by a remark to a meeting of the Institute of
Directors in April 1991 that a sherry decanter with six glasses on a silver
plated tray which sold in his shops at Pounds 4.95 was 'total crap'. The
comment hit sales in the shops.
In August this year, Ratners reported a pre-tax loss of Pounds 122.3m for
the year to February 1, compared with a profit of Pounds 112.1m the previous
year. It announced a change in marketing strategy, a plan to close 330
shops, and said its bankers had agreed to extend its loans until June next
year.
Mr Ratner holds 790,000 Ratners shares, 0.3 per cent of the company.
Cut price Midas, Page 24
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 1
</PAGE>
