<DOCNO>FT924-5636</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKZCGADGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921126
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 NOV 92 / Tate &amp; Lyle falls as US weather hits sales and crops
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TATE &amp; LYLE, the sugar and sweeteners group, announced a drop in pre-tax
profits from Pounds 230.8m to Pounds 189.5m for the year to end-September,
with poor weather in the US blamed for much of the fall. The reduction was
the company's first profit reverse for 14 years.
However, Mr Stephen Brown, chief executive, said he was 'extremely bullish
about this year' and expected a 'rebound in profits'. The eight weeks
trading since the September year-end underscored this view, he said. The
shares rose 12p to 368p.
A final dividend of 8p is proposed, up from 7p, to give a total of 12p, a
7.1 per cent rise. The dividend is covered more than twice by fully diluted
earnings per share of 26.2p, down 20.6 per cent. Mr Neil Shaw, chairman,
said the dividend increase reflected the 'long-term cash generative nature
of the business'.
He said the group faced no lack of opportunities and had made heavy
investments, for instance in eastern Europe, but these were yet to make a
return.
Developments in the common agricultural policy, the Gatt talks and the North
American Free Trade Agreement were not negative and some might be positive
for the group, he said.
Group sales rose 3.2 per cent to Pounds 3.4bn, but problems in Tate's US
sugar and corn sweetener subsidiaries hit pre-interest profits, which fell
from Pounds 280.5m to Pounds 237.4m. At this level the net interest charge
of Pounds 47.9m, down from Pounds 49.7m, was still covered 5 times.
Staley, Tate's US high fructose corn syrup business, suffered as poor summer
weather depressed soft drinks sales and overcapacity in the industry put
pressure on prices. Pre-interest profits in the division fell from Pounds
96.8m to Pounds 65.3m. A new chief executive has been hired.
At Western Sugar, the US sugar beet business, a frost followed by a thaw
damaged the beet. Western was barely profitable and profits from the US
sugar division, which includes cane, fell from Pounds 49.3m to Pounds 30.9m.
Good performances were seen in UK sugar refining, where productivity rose,
and a record tonnage was processed in Portugal, where Tate has increased its
stake in Alcantara from 62 per cent to 97 per cent, and at Bundaberg, the
Australian sugar business acquired in June 1991.
Lex, Page 22; Sweetened by market growth, Page 24
</TEXT>
