<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Tories beat off attack on EC role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government last night survived a Labour attack on its discharge of
Britain's presidency of the European Community, which is due to end next
month. It secured a Comons majority of 50 (312-262), in favour of its
policy.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, intervened in the closing stages of the
debate to dismiss suggestions by Labour leaders that the summit meeting due
to open in Edinburgh on December 11 could result in adverse changes to the
arrangements negotiated by Mrs Margaret Thatcher, the former prime minister,
to reduce Britain's contribution to the EC budget.
'We are not prepared to accept a change,' Mr Lamont insisted.
Sir John Cope, paymaster general, who wound up the debate, said Britain's
underlying net contribution through the public sector to the EC budget was
now running at some Pounds 2bn a year. He stressed it would be much higher
without the abatement negotiated by Mrs Thatcher.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, assured the House that there would
be radical changes in the operation of the EC, with more decisions taken at
national level, as a result of the British presidency.
He praised the role of Mr John Major, the prime minister, in opening the way
for a wider agreement on liberalising world trade which,coupled with the
steps taken to ensure a single European market by the start of next year,
would be seen as 'massive achievements'.
Mr Hurd dismissed remarks by 'flustered' French politicians attacking the
ineffectiveness of the British presidency and urged Labour MPs to be more
careful in expressing similar sentiments.
That did not deter Mr John Cunningham, shadow foreign secretary, from
arguing that the humiliating and total collapse of government policies in
the wake of sterling's forced withdrawal from the exchange rate mechanism
had put Britain on the 'sideline in Europe'.
He ended an appraisal of the achievements of the British presidency, based
on the benchmarks set by the government itself, by awarding one mark out of
10.
Labour MPs encouraged Mr Nick Budgen, the prominent Euro-sceptic Tory MP for
Wolverhampton South-West when he complained that the whips had used a 'hard
ball' when seeking to contain the recent revolt by Conservative backbenchers
over the Maastricht treaty when the government survived by just three votes.
</TEXT>
