FT  25 NOV 92 / Maltese currency devalued
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GODFREY GRIMA
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   VALLETTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MALTA last night devalued the Maltese lira by 10 per cent in a move
apparently hastened by this week's devaluation of the Spanish and Portuguese
currencies.
The lira, which was yesterday quoted at 1.89 to the pound sterling, had been
widely regarded as pegged at an unrealistically high rate by successive
governments.
The decision was announced by Finance Minister John Dalli while presenting a
LM400m budget in parliament for the coming year.
He said devaluation would lessen the impact of worldwide economic slowdown
on the island's developing economy.
It would also help meet the challenge of more competitive Mediterranean
holidays and preserve the island's attractions as an investment base, Mr
Dalli added.
Previously Malta has steered clear of devaluation for fear of the spiralling
cost of imports, on which Malta is heavily dependent.
