<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Careers 'high priority' for women
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GETTING on in their job is becoming more of a priority for women under 35
than having children, the National Council of Women of Great Britain said
yesterday.
The survey by the council, an umbrella organisation for more than 100
groups, shows that only a small minority of women aged between 16 and 44
thought a women needed a child to feel fulfilled.
When asked what they would like to spend more time on, families came third
on every woman's list. Only a fifth wanted to devote more hours to their
home life. Time for hobbies and educational opportunities scored twice as
highly.
Women also believed that society undervalued the work they did in the home
and with their families.
Superwoman Keeps Going - Understanding the Female Web. NCW, 36 Danbury
Street, London N1 8JU. Pounds 3.25.
