<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow rallies on strong durable
goods orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stock markets rallied strongly in heavy trading on unexpectedly good
economic news, although late selling took the edge off some of the gains,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 25.66 at 3,248.70, well
below earlier highs when the index had been up 40 points. The more broadly
based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 finished 2.47 higher at 427.59, the Amex composite
0.79 firmer at 391.53, and the Nasdaq composite up 7.10 at 645.94, a new
all-time high. Turnover on the NYSE was extremely heavy at 242m shares, and
rises outpaced declines by 1,113 to 707.
After a relatively quiet opening, prices moved higher after the Commerce
Department said that durable goods orders in October rose by 3.9 per cent,
and the Conference Board that its index of consumer confidence had climbed
from 54.6 in October to 65.5 in November.
Both reports were much more positive about the economy than analysts had
been expecting. Investors were initially hesitant about responding to the
durable goods orders number - one of the most unreliable of the monthly
indicators, and heavily affected by volatile defence and civilian aircraft
orders - but the consumer confidence figures were more convincing.
Cyclicals and other blue-chips posted especially big gains. International
Paper rose Dollars 1 5/8 to Dollars 62 5/8 , IBM climbed Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 64 7/8 , Procter &amp; Gamble put on Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 54 5/8 ,
Caterpillar rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 54 and Minnesota Mining &amp;
Manufacturing firmed Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 101 3/4 .
The effects of some of Monday's big corporate announcements continued to
wash through the market. Martin Marietta, which rose sharply on Monday on
news of its Dollars 3.05bn acquisition of General Electric's aerospace
interests, suffered a reaction, dropping Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 62 1/8 .
GE, which had also risen on the news, fared better, firming Dollars  3/4 to
Dollars 82 7/8 .
Westinghouse was another stock to run into profit-taking. Following a big
rise on Monday's major restructuring news, the industrial conglomerate fell
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 11, erasing part of Monday's advance.
On the Nasdaq market, Dell Computer rose Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 35 1/2 on
the news that the Securities and Exchange Commission is looking into recent
trading patterns in the stock, particularly the gains that followed its
earnings last week, and the sharp losses which came after Kidder Peabody,
the broking house, issued a report raising questions about improper
accounting of foreign currency trading activities at Dell.
Microsoft jumped Dollars 3 to Dollars 91 1/2 in turnover of 4.3m shares
after Mr Rick Sherlund, who cut his earnings forecasts for the computer
group on Monday, said that his new estimates were 'likely too conservative.'
Canada
Final closing volume on the Toronto Stock Exchange was 31.92m shares,
including after-hours trading volume of 129,700 shares.
PWA Corp fell 24 cents to CDollars 1.21 and traders said that a federal
government promise to provide the company with up to CDollars 50m in
financial aid was not enough to support the share price.
