<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NICKEL prices resumed their upward trend at the London Metal Exchange
yesterday, though never challenging the highs reached on Monday. The three
months position, which touched Dollars 5,650 a tonne before selling set in
on Monday, closed yesterday at Dollars 5,557.50 a tonne up Dollars 30 on the
day. ZINC prices, having absorbed early stop-loss selling, found good mixed
buying interest. Three months zinc hit Dollars 1,051 a tonne at one point
before recovering to close at Dollars 1,064.75 a tonne, up Dollars 2.50 on
the day. It moved further ahead in kerb (after hours) trading to Dollars
1,068 a tonne. Three months ALUMINIUM continued Monday's rally to reach
Dollars 1,213 a tonne at one stage, but by the end of the kerb session
hedging sales and profit-taking had pulled it back to Dollars 1,200 a tonne,
down Dollars 6. LEAD prices softened initially in response to a 4,350-tonne
LME stocks rise, believed to represent arrivals of CIS metal. But once the
three months price had dipped to Pounds 312 a tonne, trade buying and
short-covering saw last business at Pounds 315.
Compiled from Reuters
