FT  25 NOV 92 / International Company News: Hachette revises Matra terms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HACHETTE, the heavily indebted French media group, has revised the terms of
its proposed merger with Matra, the defence electronics company also
controlled by the Lagardere family, and finalised plans for its own FFr900m
(Dollars 165.5m) capital increase.
Under the new merger terms the shareholders in Matra, which has proved more
robust than the loss-making Hachette over the past year, will receive 13 of
the latter's shares for every five of their existing shares.
This represents a marked improvement over the original merger terms in which
Matra's investors would have been given five Hachette shares for two shares
in the defence electronics group. Matra's shareholders will receive a
package of shares in Hachette worth just over FFr1,240 for Matra shares
worth FFr973.50
Since the announcement of the original terms Hachette has continued to
perform poorly. It has also discovered the extent of its exposure to La
Cinq, the French television station that collapsed earlier this year, in
which it was the managing shareholder with 25 per cent of the equity.
A French court on Monday ruled that Hachette had to inject FFr100m into La
Cinq. Hachette has already made provisions of FFr3.54bn to cover its
liabilities on the station. Mr Philippe Camus, chairman of MMB, Hachette's
main shareholder, said yesterday that these provisions were 'more than
adequate'.
Mr Camus also disclosed the final terms of Hachette's proposed capital
increase. The company plans to raise FFr900m by issuing 11.8m shares at
FFr76.30 each. The price of the issue compares with Hachette's suspended
share price of FFr95.40.
Hachette's shares are expected to resume trading on the Paris stock market
today after being suspended on Monday pending yesterday's announcement. The
shares of Matra and MMB were also suspended on Monday at FFr194.70 and FFr82
respectively.
