<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Observer: Hobson's choice
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The theatrical world gathered in strength yesterday at the actors' church,
St Paul's, Covent Garden, for the thanksgiving service for Sir Harold
Hobson, long the drama critic of the Sunday Times, and the man who helped
build the reputations of such writers as Samuel Beckett and Harold Pinter.
It is not only for his enthusiasm that Hobson is remembered; he also knew
about seat prices. 'If you have only 17 shillings and sixpence left in the
world,' he once wrote, 'go and see Waiting for Godot. If you have 35
shillings, see it twice.' Beckett's play was thus saved from being
prematurely withdrawn from the London stage.
</TEXT>
