<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Licence fee likely to be retained: Tory backbenchers call
for new funding structure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TELEVISION licence fee is 'likely' to be the basis on which the BBC's
future is to be secured, Mr Peter Brooke, national heritage secretary, told
MPs yesterday.
Replying to questions on yesterday's green paper, Mr Brooke said: 'In terms
of financing the BBC, there is no obvious improvement on the licence fee.'
His remarks followed calls from Tory backbenchers to consider implementing a
fee structure that did not oblige viewers to pay for programmes they did not
watch.
Mr Brooke sought to reassure MPs on the government's commitment to
public-service broadcasting, saying 'we strongly envisage' that the concept
would play a key role in the BBC's activities at the end of the consultation
period.
He declined a request from Mr Roy Hattersley, the former Labour deputy
leader, to 'specifically reject' the notion that the BBC might be limited to
a narrow range of programmes. But Mr Brooke said it was important that
Britain should emerge from the consultation with 'a major production base'.
Mrs Ann Clwyd, shadow heritage secretary, said her party remained
'completely committed' to the concept of public-service broadcasting. Labour
would oppose any attempt to privatise the BBC 'even at its edges'.
Mrs Clywd asked whether the government would support index-linking the
licence fee for a minimum of 10 years, as a means of ensuring stability and
enabling the organisation to be 'free from any attempt at editorial control
by the government or anyone else'.
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Robert Maclennan, home affairs spokesman, said
there was a danger the BBC would be put on 'starvation rations' and its
public-sector role attenuated. The BBC's 'firm financial independence' was
the 'basis of its role as a defender of free speech', he said.
</TEXT>
