<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Girls catch up in maths results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOYS have only a slight edge over girls in maths performance at GCSE, while
girls have a significant lead in English, a report said yesterday, Andrew
Adonis writes.
Historically, boys have outperformed girls at maths by a large margin, but
an analysis of this year's GCSE results shows that boys gained only 3 per
cent more higher grades (A to C) than girls, while girls gained 14 per cent
more higher grades in English than boys.
The report says the relative performance of the sexes in maths is
attributable partly to 'the tendency for a higher proportion of girls than
boys to be entered for the safer intermediate examination papers rather than
the more challenging papers which lead to the top grades'.
The report was based on research carried out by the University of London for
the School Examinations and Assessment Council, a government advisory body.
</TEXT>
