<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Exports strategy to be unveiled
today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR RICHARD NEEDHAM, the trade minister, will today announce details of a
national strategy for export promotion intended to boost Britain's share of
international trade by Pounds 10bn a year and reverse the decline of capital
exporters in the developing world.
The plan, intended to quell complaints that the government lacks a clear
strategy for economic recovery, aims to bring coherence to an existing array
of national and local policies rather than outline new initiatives.
It comes at a time of rising concern over Britain's export performance,
which in spite of what amounts to a 13 per cent devaluation since Black
Wednesday two months ago continues to lag behind the trend in imports.
Exports in October were Pounds 9.1bn, a record for 1992, and up by 4.6 per
cent on September - but more than matched by a 5 per cent rise in imports to
Pounds 10.2bn.
The 'Needham plan' to be outlined today will involve:
Regeneration of exhibition facilities, starting with support for the 1995
'West Midlands Year of Celebration', based on Birmingham's National
Exhibition Centre.
Corralling leading exporters to 'godfather' smaller companies, showing them
how to make headway in overseas markets.
Using the Department of Trade and Industry's industrial competitiveness
division to 'make sure the government knows what the rest of the world is
doing'.
Ensuring that adequate export credit cover is available to exporters 'with
the maximum gearing from this and the Aid for Trade Provision to bring in
behind capital goods exporters'.
Boosting the 'one-stop shop' operations in the British regions as outlined
by Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, enabling exporters to
deal with all procedures in one location.
Mr Needham will acknowledge that 'big industry' exporters have lost ground
in markets in the developing world, from almost Dollars 550m in 1986 (a 7
per cent share of total Dollars 7.8bn trade in capital goods) to Dollars
532m in 1990 (a 5 per cent share of Dollars 10.7bn).
The government's aim - based on projections formulated by the Confederation
of British Industry in March - is to boost Britain's share of international
trade from 5.3 per cent in 1990 to 6.3 per cent by the turn of the century.
That would add Pounds 10bn to exports at current prices and eliminate the
country's visible trade deficit, the CBI said.
Capital goods exporters have complained vehemently over the past year that
the high cost of export credit insurance, and limits to cover in buoyant
markets such as Hong Kong, China and Malaysia, have undermined their
competitiveness in these markets.
The government went part of the way to meeting complaints in its Autumn
Statement two weeks ago when it announced a Pounds 700m increase in export
credit cover available for such markets. But it has resisted pressure to cut
premium rates, partly because of a conviction that the devaluation of
sterling and cuts in interest rates will have provided exporters with the
stimulus they need.
'This is not a strategy for the next fortnight,' Mr Needham said yesterday,
'It's a strategy that is to embed itself throughout the trading base of the
UK, at a local level, within government, between departments of government,
and in their relations with industry and overseas. To get the local
infrastructure in place is going to take a bit of time.'
</TEXT>
