FT  25 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: MPs may see papers on Iraq policy
meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAPERS RELATING to a ministerial meeting at which it was decided to
recommend revising the government's policy on British exports to Iraq may be
made available to MPs after Mr Michael Heseltine's reference to them in
Monday night's Commons debate.
The trade and industry secretary alluded to the papers in connection with a
suggestion made by Labour's Mr Robin Cook that the government may never have
intended to announce such a change to parliament.
He said they showed that Mr Cook was 'diametrically wrong' and that
ministers had concluded that any change should be announced.
Mr Heseltine's use of the papers prompted interventions from Mr Tony Benn,
Labour MP for Chesterfield, who said that where government documents were
quoted 'they must be placed on the table of the House'.
Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, said yesterday that the whole of the
document from which Mr Heseltine quoted would be 'laid before the House'.
The meeting - on July 19 1990, just two weeks before Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait - recommended that policy be revised without permitting the export of
lethal equipment.
In a separate development, it also emerged that Mr Heseltine asked for
changes to the 'public interest immunity' certificate for which he was
responsible. It referred to papers the government wanted to be kept secret
in the Matrix Churchill trial.
His decision to insist on alterations before he signed has further
encouraged his supporters to believe he will be cleared completely by Lord
Justice Scott's inquiry into the arms-to-Iraq affair.
But the differences between Mr Heseltine's certificate and those signed by
three other government ministers may raise questions about why similar fears
were not raised by his colleagues.
Mr Heseltine made clear that 'whether in fact all or part of any individual
document or documents should be disclosed is a matter for the court'.
He stressed it was up to the court to decide if 'there is a counter-vailing
public interest that the requirements of doing justice in this case require
their (the documents') disclosure'.
He also stressed that he believed he had no choice but to sign.
</TEXT>
