<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Parliament and Politics: Links with unions face fresh
scrutiny
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE is mounting from Labour's so-called 'moderniser' faction for
wide-ranging revisions to an internal working party's proposals on how to
update its traditional links with the unions.
Leaked copies of the committee's outline final report reveal that it has
stopped short of approving a one-member, one-vote system for the selection
of MPs in spite of firm backing for the reform from Mr John Smith, the party
leader.
Instead, the committee is looking at creating a form of associate membership
for union members who pay the political levy and also express support for
Labour. These would carry voting rights.
Advocates of such a change argue that it will maintain the broad base of the
party among ordinary people and dilute the impact of activists, who are
often unrepresentative of wider public opinion.
They also claim it could lay the foundations for the creation of a mass
party as associates are persuaded to upgrade to full membership.
Opponents of the scheme say it is bureaucratic, costly, creates a divisive
dual-status membership structure and might possibly be open to manipulation
by undemocratic elements within the unions.
They also point out that it might offer the Conservative government a
pretext to change the law to insist that unionists opt in to paying the
political levy rather than opt out of paying it - potentially crippling
Labour's income.
One member of the NEC said yesterday that the plan would be 'disastrous' in
terms of presentation and was substantially worse than existing
arrangements.
</TEXT>
