<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Sex discrimination reported at Bar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN barristers face substantial discrimination affecting their chances of
becoming a Queen's counsel or a judge, according to an independent survey of
sex equality in the profession.
The survey, commissioned jointly by the Bar Council and the Lord
Chancellor's Department, is the first large-scale study of sex
discrimination in an important profession in this country.
It found 'substantial evidence of early and continuing unequal treatment
between the sexes'; 'a discrepancy between male and female perceptions of
equality issues'; and 'a marked tendency of failure to recognise this as a
problem by those who occupy the higher levels - heads of chambers
(barristers' offices) and judges.'
Sixty per cent of women respondents reported disadvantage on the ground of
their sex. More than 70 per cent felt under pressure to perform better than
men and that their performance was watched more closely.
Women felt sex discrimination was the second-most prevalent source of
discrimination and men ranked it fifth. Race discrimination was ranked first
by both groups. Women face particular obstacles in being selected for
traineeships.
The report recommends action by both the Bar and the Lord Chancellor's
Department, which has overall responsibility for the appointment of QCs and
judges.
Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, welcomed the study yesterday.
Without Prejudice? Sex Equality at the Bar and in the Judiciary, TMS
Management Consultants, 87 Southbourne Coast Rd, Bournemouth BH6 4DX.
</TEXT>
