<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Charter poised to include GPs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is about to extend the National Health Service Patient's
Charter to family doctors and other areas of primary care.
So far, the Department of Health's contribution to the Citizen's Charter has
concentrated on hospital services. But 90 per cent of medical consultations
begin and end with general practitioners, and the decision to involve them
in the charter has a number of significant implications.
In 1990 the government introduced a new performance-related contract for
family doctors which, among other things, was intended to improve patient
choice and make it easier for people to change GPs. One of the difficulties
of extending choice has been the absence of clearly understood common
criteria to help patients assess whether the services provided by a
particular GP are reasonable.
The charter proposals will set out a range of standards including maximum
waiting times for urgent consultations with GPs; waiting times for routine
consultations and waiting times to see a chosen doctor in a group practice.
Other factors, such as availability of health education services and
facilities for children in GPs' surgeries, will be included.
The primary-care proposals will break new ground for the charter concept
because GPs are independent contractors rather than NHS employees.
That means that their involvement in the charter programme must be
voluntary.
The charter arrangements will be fortified by a set of national standards
for family health services authorities, the statutory bodies responsible for
administering primary care.
</TEXT>
