<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Industry's financial health 'on the mend'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON, Industrial Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE financial health of industry is on the mend, a leading group of risk
assessors said yesterday. It reported that the proportion of quoted
companies at risk of failure was falling for the first time since 1988.
Syspas, the London-based consultants, said industrial companies showing a
decreasing risk of failure in the past three months outnumber those showing
higher risk by 50 per cent, a reversal of past trends.
The Syspas method involves defining the financial characteristics of
companies that have failed in the past and finding how far existing
companies conform to that pattern. Syspas claims to have predicted the
present recession at the beginning of 1989, based on the rising number of
companies shown to be at risk. It also identified Maxwell Communication
Corporation as 'beyond saving in its present form' some time before the
death of Robert Maxwell in November last year.
At the peak of the boom in 1988, the Syspas model suggested that 11 per cent
of all quoted industrial companies showed at least some risk of failure. The
figure then rose to a peak of 26 per cent in May of this year. The present
figure is put at 25 per cent.
</TEXT>
