FT  25 NOV 92 / Clearer statements urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPOSED regulations on the contents of summary financial statements are too
prescriptive, the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales
has warned.
In a letter to the Department of Trade and Industry, the institute's company
law committee argues that summary statements should be able to improve
communication by using simpler language than required in full accounts.
It also says there should be separate disclosure of securities and
investments such as loans and advances to banks and to customers in the
proposed summary balance sheet.
The submission follows a consultative document issued by the DTI last month
on summary financial statements which proposed extending the guidelines to
debenture and loan stock holders and partial owners of shares.
The statements - permitted since April 1990 - must cover basic
profit-and-loss accounts, directors' remuneration and an outline balance
sheet with contingent liabilities.
In a letter to Companies House, the government's corporate information
depository based in Wales, the company law committee calls for clearer
guidance on filing accounts for EC member-state companies with UK branches
and also non-EC companies which have a 'place of business' in the UK.
</TEXT>
