FT  25 NOV 92 / UN opposes Cuban embargo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, UN Correspondent and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations general assembly last night called for an end to the US
embargo against Cuba, imposed some three decades ago when the government of
Fidel Castro seized billions of dollars' worth of US assets, Michael
Littlejohns, UN Correspondent in New York, and Agencies report.
Canada and Mexico, parties to the new free-trade agreement with the US, were
among 59 states voting for the measure, which Cuba drafted. The US
vigorously canvassed against the resolution but was rebuffed largely because
of new legislation signed by US President George Bush last month which
extended the embargo to foreign sub-sidiaries of US corporations and foreign
commercial shipping.
Many countries that might otherwise have sided with the US moved to the
sidelines, including EC members. There were 71 abstentions and only Israel
and Romania sided with the US.
Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN secretary-general, has been asked to prepare a
report on implementation of the resolution in time for next year's assembly
session. Unlike mandatory Security Council resolutions, assembly decisions
are not binding.
</TEXT>
