FT  25 NOV 92 / Pact on ozone layer set to be tightened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A WORLD-WIDE treaty to protect the ozone layer of the atmosphere looked set
early today to be tightened for the third time in its five-year life, writes
Bronwen Maddox in Copenhagen. This follows negotiations by ministers and
officials at a three-day United Nations conference.
Mr David Maclean, UK environment minister, said: 'We think we have agreed a
package that has something for everyone.' The main part of the new version
of the 1987 Montreal protocol, to be formally agreed today, is a commitment
by industrialised countries to phase out certain damaging chemicals by 1996
instead of the previous date of 2000.
The turning point came when industrialised countries pledged up to Dollars
500m (Pounds 330m) on top of Dollars 240m already committed to help
developing countries phase out chemicals that harm the ozone layer. In
return, developing countries look set to phase out some chemicals by 2006,
four years earlier than previously agreed.
