<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / Pension tax rebates to be altered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has announced plans to encourage personal pension holders to
stay out of the state pension plan.
From 1996 it will offer age-related tax rebates which will be more generous
to older people. The move is widely seen as an admission that the present
system may not reduce the cost of the state earnings related pension scheme
(Serps).
Under the present regime, men in their late 40s receive too little tax
rebate to make a personal pension worthwhile, and those who have them are
advised to give up personal pensions and rejoin Serps.
But the government still intends to reduce tax breaks for the young, a move
which the insurance industry fears will discourage them from buying personal
pensions.
'The government is committed to considering options for a new system of
rebates related to age to come into effect from April 1996 for personal
pension holders,' the Department of Social Security said.
The government, which had rejected all age-related rebates a year ago, will
now consider extending tax incentives to occupational schemes as well.
The move comes as the government's own actuarial department has produced
figures showing that if the government were to maintain its current policy,
tax rebates would be bound to fall over the next 30 years so that only those
in their late 20s would choose personal pensions. The present system offers
the same rebate to all - a structure which encourages people to rejoin the
state pension system as they grow older and which saves the government very
little money.
The National Audit Office has estimated that between 1988 and 1993, personal
pensions rebates cost Pounds 5.9bn more than they saved in potential social
security expense.
Much of the insurance industry has opposed the introduction of age-related
rebates because it is felt they will offer young people tax incentives too
small to encourage them to choose a personal pension.
Because lower contributions to pensions schemes are required from young
people, the current flat rate rebate system allows them to buy a far more
generous personal pension than they could obtain in the state system.
However, some insurance companies support the concept because they believe
it will allow them to retain pension clients longer. 'We will be able to
hang on to our premium-paying clients,' said Mr Ron Spill, head of pensions
at Legal and General, one of Britain's largest providers of personal
pensions.
Currently, personal pension holders who opt out of Serps are entitled to a
rebate of 5.8 per cent of tax of national average earnings. By next April,
the government intends to cut that to 4.8 per cent of earnings and only
those over the age of 30 will be eligible for the maximum tax savings.
The current system has encouraged 4.7m people to take out personal pensions,
but it is expected that a large minority of those will opt back into the
Serps system when the less generous rebates take effect.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
