<HEADLINE>
FT  25 NOV 92 / International Company News: Court extends O &amp; Y protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER, LOUISE KEHOE and NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AN Ontario bankruptcy court last night approved a motion by Olympia &amp; York
Developments to extend the period the developer is protected from creditors
in order to allow time for a debt restructuring plan to be negotiated,
Reuter reports.
It ordered the stay of protection to be extended to February 1 from December
30, and the dates creditors will vote on O&amp;Y's proposed plan to between
January 11 and 15 from November 25 to 30.
O&amp;Y and its creditors are still working on developing a plan to restructure
about CDollars 8.6m (USDollars 6.82m) in debts on its Canadian assets. A new
plan is now scheduled to be presented to the court by December 14.
DELL Computer has received an 'informal request' from the Securities and
Exchange Commission (SEC) for information and documents relating to trading
patterns in the company's shares, writes Louise Kehoe in San Francisco.
The personal computer manufacturer said that the SEC's request was focused
on trading surrounding the company's third-quarter earnings announced last
Thursday and upon 'subsequent events prompted by remarks made by a Kidder
Peabody analyst on the following day'.
AMERICAN Re, the Princeton-based reinsurance company that was bought out
earlier this year from Aetna Life and Casualty by its management and
Kolhberg, Kravis Roberts, the leveraged buy-out specialists, is coming back
to the stock market, writes Nikki Tait.
The insurance company announced yesterday that it planned to make an initial
public offering - or flotation - of ordinary shares, to be completed by
early 1993.
</TEXT>
